A few points:

1. Dont use `setTimeout()`. You can only guess at the timeout value. 5000, or anything else, might be too long or too short. It&#39;s pretty simple to allow the promises returned by `fetch()` and `response.json()` to determine the timing - no guesswork.

1. Allow your functions to accept parameters and return results. By doing so caller functions can work directly with returned values/objects and outer members, eg `dAmt`, `dOOP`, `dGM`, `fAmt`, `fOOP`, `fGM`, can be avoided; most will become inner members of `getConvertedAmounts()`.

1. As `getConversionAsync` is asynchronous, and `getConvertedAmounts()` calls `getConversionAsync()`, `getConvertedAmounts()` is also (by definition) asynchronous.

1. There&#39;s no need to initialize `output`. Error handling in `getConversionAsync()` can be used to set default values for the conversions if any of the `fetch()` calls fails.

1. The population of `output` can be proceduralized in a few lines of code.

